narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned so much in this class! I already knew a decent amount of HTML, CSS, and javascript, but my peers who knew nothing going in said it was a perfect way to learn. I improved my fluency and understanding of all the programs and also expanded my idea of what a website could be. On top of that, I still learned a lot that I didn't know before. The professor and TA were very nice and helped us with any coding questions. Very interesting conversations as well.
I learned how to use HTML, CSS, and the basics of JavaScript to code personal, artistic webpages.
I learned the basics of coding and design. More than technical skills, the course develops your way of thinking and perceiving.
coding skills and design skills
website technical skills, learned about the landscape of interactive design, thought critically of website design and conformity/uniformity
I learned how to navigate conversations surrounding art in our increasingly digital world and how to think about digital art in terms of design, content, and scale.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Some of the discussions could have used better starter questions to inspire dialogue, but every discussion still was intriguing regardless. More examples of the type of work expected for each major project would be helpful. I was often scared I didn't do enough, or too much, for the projects. I usually was fine, but would appreciate more guidance in terms of direction of projects.

The strengths of this course were its classroom environment and its workload. Everyone, including the instructors, were so kind and enthusiastic and willing to share bits of themselves. This class also had a very manageable workload with very few restrictions with regard to artistic direction.
amazing curriculum, amazing teachers -- honestly I wouldn't change anything.

This course was paced super well for a summer course. The readings led to engaging conversation without bogging the course down with too much content, and the projects allowed space for individually motivated exploration of course content while also maintaining a sustainable pace.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, I would! You'll def have fun taking this course, and you get so much freedom in your projects that you'll always be interested in the content.

If you have never taken an art class, or coded before, or coded websites before, definitely take this class. Hopefully the next teacher will be equally as great as Mianwei, but the content of this course is great on its own.
Yes, the instructor is great and it really changes the way you think about design and the intent behind a website.
Yes -- one of the best classes I've taken at Yale. Learned so much without stress and anxiety.

YES. This course, especially in the summer allows you to engage academically with interesting concepts about technology while still having space for personal reflection and rest. Best of all, there is lots of space to take individual initiative with your learning within the personally guided reading responses, discussions, and projects.

narratives.question_text: How will you use the knowledge and skills you learned in this course in your future endeavors?
comments: I will always think of my audience when designing a website now.
I will be using it in making good looking websites.
The knowledge and skills will greatly impact my career and my future website design (can't wait to make my own professional website), w/ interactive design elements

I will carry my knowledge of HTML and the concepts from our discussions to critically consume and engage with the internet and art more broad as I move forward. I will have my skills in using HTML in an expressive way to support me in my individual creation of new things.
